Part I - (Flights Data Exploration)¶

by Jane Harry¶

Introduction¶

This dataset reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delays, for the year 2007

  • What are the Characteristics of delayed flights? Are there certain destinations that are home to more delays or cancellations?
  • What are the characteristics of cancelled flights? Is it dependent on time or seasons?

To answer this, we look at data obatined from 7453215 flights that took place in 2007

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 7453215, rows with 19 feautures. The column names are described in the variables DataFrame above

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main points of interest are feautures that are characteristics of, or results in delayed/cancelled flights Arrival delay: Arrival delay equals the difference of the actual arrival time minus the scheduled arrival time. A flight is considered on-time when it arrives less than 15 minutes after its published arrival time.

  • The proportion of delayed/cancelled flights in different seasons of the year
  • Destination or arrival cities that are home to more delays or cancellations?
  • Airline systems with higher delays

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Months --I expect that weather which is dependent on the seasn of the year, will have the strongest effect on whether or not a flight is cancelled
  • Unique Carriers -- and certain carriers may be notorious for having delays,
  • Destinations --those areas with a far destination may have a high probability of being delayed, and;
  • departure time-- Will affect whether or not a flight experiences delay

Other than this, there weren't much differences in the monthly volume of flights. It would be im portant to compute the mnthly delay patterns, and reasons

  • Airline carriers such as AA had both high level of cancellation and departure delays

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • Surprisingly, WN, a UniqueCarrier with the highest volume of flights had a low record of cancelled flights especially when compared to AA which had a high volume of flights, and a high volume of both cancelled and delayed flights
  • I changed the Cancelled and Diverted columns into categorical datatypes
  • I subsetted the data, and selected variables where the departure delays were greater than 15. This is to assess late flights, which generally have arrival or departure time more than 15minutes the expected time respectively
  • I dropped some uneccessary columns

Conclusions¶

This an interesting dataset taht shows that flight delays are strongly dependent on weather, and Unique Carrrier. From the dataset, I could see that carriers cuch as AA wer unreliable in terms of cancellations and delays. Flights do not freuquently experience diversions and cancellations, and as the distance a flight will cover increase, the amount of time it spends in departure delay increases, up until a certain point. Further studies could be conducted independently on different years, as I was unable to do that due to memory constraintS
